    <section label="2">
     <section-title>
      Preliminaries
     </section-title>
     <paragraph label="Definition 1">
      Let {a mathematical formula}At be some fixed propositional signature, i.e., a (possibly infinite) set of propositions, and let {a mathematical formula}L(At) be the corresponding propositional language constructed using the usual connectives ∧ (and), ∨ (or), and ¬ (negation). A knowledge base {a mathematical formula}K is a finite set of formulas {a mathematical formula}K⊆L(At). Let {a mathematical formula}K be the set of all knowledge bases. If X is a formula or a set of formulas we write {a mathematical formula}At(X) to denote the set of propositions appearing in X. Semantics to a propositional language is given by interpretations and an interpretation ω on {a mathematical formula}At is a function {a mathematical formula}ω:At→{true,false}. Let {a mathematical formula}Ω(At) denote the set of all interpretations for {a mathematical formula}At. An interpretation ω satisfies (or is a model of) a proposition {a mathematical formula}a∈At, denoted by {a mathematical formula}ω⊨a, if and only if {a mathematical formula}ω(a)=true. The satisfaction relation ⊨ is extended to formulas in the usual way.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      As an abbreviation we sometimes identify an interpretation ω with its complete conjunction, i.e., if {a mathematical formula}a1,…,an∈At are those propositions that are assigned {a mathematical formula}true by ω and {a mathematical formula}an+1,…,am∈At are those propositions that are assigned {a mathematical formula}false by ω we identify ω by {a mathematical formula}a1…anan+1‾…am‾ (or any permutation of this). For example, the interpretation {a mathematical formula}ω1 on {a mathematical formula}{a,b,c} with {a mathematical formula}ω(a)=ω(c)=true and {a mathematical formula}ω(b)=false is abbreviated by {a mathematical formula}ab‾c.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      For {a mathematical formula}Φ⊆L(At) we also define {a mathematical formula}ω⊨Φ if and only if {a mathematical formula}ω⊨ϕ for every {a mathematical formula}ϕ∈Φ. Define furthermore the set of models {a mathematical formula}Mod(X)={ω∈Ω(At)|ω⊨X} for every formula or set of formulas X. If {a mathematical formula}Mod(X)=∅ we also write {a mathematical formula}X⊨⊥ and say that X is inconsistent.
     </paragraph>
