     <section label="3.6">
      <section-title>
       Distance-based inconsistency measures
      </section-title>
      <paragraph>
       In [8] three families of inconsistency measures are defined that are based on a notion of distance to consistency. More precisely, an interpretation distance d is a function {a mathematical formula}d:Ω(At)×Ω(At)→[0,∞) that satisfies (let {a mathematical formula}ω,ω′,ω″∈Ω(At))
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="1.">
        {a mathematical formula}d(ω,ω′)=0 if and only if {a mathematical formula}ω=ω′ (reflexivity),
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="2.">
        {a mathematical formula}d(ω,ω′)=d(ω′,ω) (symmetry), and
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="3.">
        {a mathematical formula}d(ω,ω″)≤d(ω,ω′)+d(ω′,ω″) (triangle inequality).
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       One prominent example of such a distance is the Dalal distance{a mathematical formula}dd defined via{a mathematical formula} for all {a mathematical formula}ω,ω′∈Ω(At). In other words, {a mathematical formula}dd(ω,ω′) is the number of propositions where ω and {a mathematical formula}ω′ assign different truth values. If {a mathematical formula}X⊆Ω(At) is a set of interpretations we define {a mathematical formula}dd(X,ω)=minω′∈X⁡dd(ω′,ω) (if {a mathematical formula}X=∅ we define {a mathematical formula}dd(X,ω)=∞). While [8] consider arbitrary distances, we will focus here on the Dalal distance for reasons of simplicity.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       The basic idea of the approaches in [8] is to measure and aggregate the distances of the models of the formulas in a knowledge base {a mathematical formula}K. For example, if a knowledge base {a mathematical formula}K has two formulas and their models have a large distance to each other, then {a mathematical formula}K should be regarded as more inconsistent compared to a knowledge base {a mathematical formula}K′ with two formulas, where this is not the case. More precisely, the first approach from [8] considered here seeks an interpretation ω such that the sum of all distances of the sets of models to ω is minimal.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Example 9">
       The Σ-distance inconsistency measure{a mathematical formula}IdalalΣ:K→R≥0∞ is defined as{a mathematical formula} for {a mathematical formula}K∈K. Another approach of [8] is to seek an interpretation ω such that the maximum distance of the sets of models is minimal. The max-distance inconsistency measure{a mathematical formula}Idalalmax:K→R≥0∞ is defined as{a mathematical formula} for {a mathematical formula}K∈K. The final approach of [8] is to minimize the number of formulas, where their corresponding sets of models have a positive distance. The hit-distance inconsistency measure{a mathematical formula}Idalalhit:K→R≥0∞ is defined as{a mathematical formula} for {a mathematical formula}K∈K.We continue Example 1 and consider{a mathematical formula} Observe that for the interpretation {a mathematical formula}ω1=ab‾cd∈Ω({a,b,c,d}) we have{a mathematical formula} and therefore {a mathematical formula}∑α∈K1dd(Mod(α),ω1)=1. There is no other interpretation {a mathematical formula}ω′ with a smaller total distance, so we have {a mathematical formula}IdalalΣ(K1)=1. Furthermore, we have {a mathematical formula}maxα∈K1⁡dd(Mod(α),ω1)=1 and there is also no other interpretation {a mathematical formula}ω′ with a smaller maximum distance. Hence, we have {a mathematical formula}Idalalmax(K1)=1 and similarly {a mathematical formula}Idalalhit(K1)=1. For {a mathematical formula}K2 we obtain{a mathematical formula} with a similar argumentation as above. For {a mathematical formula}Idalalhit(K2) observe that every interpretation ω must always falsify exactly one formula in {a mathematical formula}{a,¬a} and exactly one formula in {a mathematical formula}{b,¬b}. Therefore we obtain {a mathematical formula}Idalalhit(K2)=2.
      </paragraph>
     </section>
     <section label="3.7">
      <section-title>
       Proof-based inconsistency measures
      </section-title>
      <paragraph>
       The final measure we consider in this paper is the proof-based measure from [16]. The basic idea is to count, for all propositions {a mathematical formula}x∈At, both the number of minimal proofs for x and its negation ¬x. If there are many proofs for both, this indicates a large inconsistency in the knowledge base. In the context of [16] a minimal proof for {a mathematical formula}α∈{x,¬x|x∈At} in {a mathematical formula}K is a set {a mathematical formula}π⊆K such that
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="1.">
        α appears as a literal in π
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="2.">
        {a mathematical formula}π⊨α, and
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="3.">
        π is minimal wrt. set inclusion.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       Note that this definition does not require that π is consistent. In particular, the set {a mathematical formula}{a∧¬a} is a minimal proof for both a and ¬a. Note furthermore, that item 1.) requires that α appears in the exact same form in π, e.g. a appears in {a mathematical formula}a∧b but not in {a mathematical formula}¬a∧b (this is a syntactic criterion).
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Let {a mathematical formula}PmK(x) be the set of all minimal proofs of x in {a mathematical formula}K. The proof-based measure of Jabbour and Raddaoui [16] can then be defined by summing up the products of the number of minimal proofs for complementary literals.
