    <section label="4">
     <section-title>
      Expressivity characteristics
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      In the literature, inconsistency measures are usually analytically evaluated on a set of rationality postulates.{sup:2} Some basic example postulates given in [11] are the following (let {a mathematical formula}I be any inconsistency measure) Consistency{a mathematical formula}I(K)=0 if and only if {a mathematical formula}K is consistentMonotonyif {a mathematical formula}K⊆K′ then {a mathematical formula}I(K)≤I(K′)Independencefor all {a mathematical formula}α∈K, if {a mathematical formula}α∉M for every {a mathematical formula}M∈MI(K) then {a mathematical formula}I(K)=I(K∖{α}) Satisfaction of the property consistency ensures that all consistent knowledge bases receive a minimal inconsistency value and every inconsistent knowledge base receives a positive inconsistency value (we already implicitly required satisfaction of this postulate in the definition of an inconsistency measure). The postulate monotony states that the value of inconsistency can only increase when adding new information. Independence states that removing “harmless” formulas from a knowledge base does not change the value of inconsistency. Besides these three postulates a series of other postulates have been proposed in the literature, see e.g. [11], [25], [2]. However, some of these postulates are disputed as each of them usually covers only a single aspect of inconsistency, such as independence, which focuses on the role of minimal inconsistent subsets. An excellent discussion on the rationality of various postulates for inconsistency measures can be found in [2]. Besides Besnard, several other authors have also criticized the rationality of individual postulates—discussions can be found in almost all papers cited before—and so there is some disagreement on which postulates are meaningful and which are not. One the one hand this calls for more work on rationality postulates and, on the other hand, it also suggests to investigate additional means for comparison. In the following, we propose a novel quantitative approach to evaluate and compare inconsistency measures that aims at complementing the existing approach of rationality postulates.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Definition 19">
      The drastic inconsistency measure {a mathematical formula}Id (see Table 1) is usually considered as a very naive baseline approach for inconsistency measurement. Surprisingly, this measure already satisfies many rationality postulates such as consistency, monotony, and independence (the proofs are straightforward). What sets it apart from other more sophisticated inconsistency measures is that it cannot differentiate between different inconsistent knowledge bases. However, this demand is exactly what inconsistency measures are supposed to satisfy. While the qualitative behavior of inconsistency measures is being discussed quite deeply using rationality postulates, their quantitative properties in terms of expressivity have been almost neglected so far.{sup:3} With expressivity of inconsistency measures we here mean the number of different values an inconsistency measure can attain. We investigate the expressivity of inconsistency measures along four different dimensions of subclasses of knowledge bases. Let ϕ be a formula. The length{a mathematical formula}l(ϕ) of ϕ is recursively defined as{a mathematical formula}Define the following subclasses of the set of all knowledge bases {a mathematical formula}K:{a mathematical formula}
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In other words, {a mathematical formula}Kv(n) is the set of all knowledge bases that mention at most n different propositions, {a mathematical formula}Kf(n) is the set of all knowledge bases that contain at most n formulas, {a mathematical formula}Kl(n) is the set of all knowledge bases that contain only formulas with maximal length n, and {a mathematical formula}Kp(n) is the set of all knowledge bases that contain only formulas that mention at most n different propositions each. The motivation for considering these particular subclasses of knowledge bases is that each of them considers a different aspect of the size of a knowledge base. As a syntactical object, a knowledge base is a set of formulas, and both the number of formulas (considered by the class {a mathematical formula}Kf(n)) and the length of each formula ({a mathematical formula}Kl(n)) are the essential parameters that define its size. From a semantical point of view, the number of propositions appearing in each formula ({a mathematical formula}Kp(n)) and in the complete knowledge base ({a mathematical formula}Kv(n)) define the scope of the knowledge. Larger numbers for both of them also indicate larger scope and thus greater size. Inconsistency measures should adhere to the size of the knowledge base in terms of their expressivity. For example, the number of possible inconsistency values of a particular measure should not decrease when moving from a set {a mathematical formula}Kv(n) to set {a mathematical formula}Kv(n′) with {a mathematical formula}n′&gt;n, as knowledge bases with {a mathematical formula}n′ formulas should provide a larger variety in terms of inconsistency as knowledge bases of size n. Indeed, this property is true for all considered measures as {a mathematical formula}Kv(n)⊆Kv(n′) (the same holds for all classes above).
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Example 11">
      The aim of our expressivity analysis is to investigate the number of different values that a specific inconsistency measure can attain on different subclasses of knowledge bases. We formalize this idea using expressivity characteristics as follows. Let {a mathematical formula}I be an inconsistency measure and {a mathematical formula}n&gt;0. Let {a mathematical formula}α∈{v,f,l,p}. The α-characteristic{a mathematical formula}Cα(I,n) of {a mathematical formula}I wrt. n is defined as{a mathematical formula} In other words, {a mathematical formula}Cα(I,n) is the number of different inconsistency values {a mathematical formula}I assigns to knowledge bases from {a mathematical formula}Kα(n). Note that these characteristics are not always the same as the maximal value of an inconsistency measure on a specific set of knowledge bases, even if the codomain of the measure is the natural numbers. Indeed, it can be the case that intermediate values cannot be attained. Consider {a mathematical formula}Iη which has the codomain {a mathematical formula}[0,1] as each value {a mathematical formula}Iη(K) can be associated with a probability value, cf. Table 1. In Knight [17] it has already been shown that {a mathematical formula}Iη(K) is always a rational number, so {a mathematical formula}2/2∉ImIη.{sup:4} Furthermore, the possible values of {a mathematical formula}Iη are further constrained when considering specific subclasses from above. For example, for every arbitrary knowledge base {a mathematical formula}K which contains at most 2 formulas, the only possible values of {a mathematical formula}Iη(K) are 0, 1/2, 1, so we have {a mathematical formula}Cf(Iη,2)=3.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Theorem 1">
      We now come to the main contribution of this paper, which is a thorough study of the 16 considered inconsistency measures in terms of our four proposed expressivity characteristics. The α-characteristics{a mathematical formula}Cα(I,n)({a mathematical formula}α∈{f,v,l,p}) for the inconsistency measures{a mathematical formula}Id,{a mathematical formula}IMI,{a mathematical formula}IMIC,{a mathematical formula}Iη,{a mathematical formula}Ic,{a mathematical formula}ILPm,{a mathematical formula}Imc,{a mathematical formula}Ip,{a mathematical formula}Ihs,{a mathematical formula}IdalalΣ,{a mathematical formula}Idalalmax,{a mathematical formula}Idalalhit,{a mathematical formula}IDf,{a mathematical formula}IPm,{a mathematical formula}Imv, and{a mathematical formula}Incare as shown inTable 3.
