    <section label="5">
     <section-title>
      Expressivity orders
     </section-title>
     <paragraph label="Definition 25">
      Let us now come back to the original motivation of comparing inconsistency measures wrt. their expressivity. Definition 20 provides the basis for a comparative analysis of inconsistency measures wrt. their expressivity, which we address with the following definition. An inconsistency measure {a mathematical formula}I is at least as expressive as an inconsistency measure {a mathematical formula}I′ wrt. a characteristic {a mathematical formula}Cα ({a mathematical formula}α∈{f,v,l,p}), denoted by {a mathematical formula}I⪰αI′, if there is {a mathematical formula}n0∈N such that for all {a mathematical formula}n&gt;n0, {a mathematical formula}Cα(I,n)≥Cα(I′,n).
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      If both {a mathematical formula}I⪰αI′ and {a mathematical formula}I′⪰αI, we say that {a mathematical formula}I and {a mathematical formula}I′ are equally expressive wrt. {a mathematical formula}Cα and denote this by {a mathematical formula}I∼αI′. If {a mathematical formula}I⪰αI′ but not {a mathematical formula}I∼αI′ we write {a mathematical formula}I≻αI′ ({a mathematical formula}I is strictly more expressive than {a mathematical formula}I′). Note that the expressivity order ⪰ is not to be confused with the refinement order ⊑ sometimes used for pairwise comparisons of inconsistency measures, see e.g. [31]. The refinement order ⊑ is defined as {a mathematical formula}I1⊑I2 iff {a mathematical formula}I2(K)≥I2(K′) implies {a mathematical formula}I1(K)≥I1(K′) for all {a mathematical formula}K, {a mathematical formula}K′. If {a mathematical formula}I1⊑I2 this means that {a mathematical formula}I2 is a refinement of {a mathematical formula}I1. Note that {a mathematical formula}⪰α compares measures in a quantitative way and also allows comparison of measures that induce totally different orders on knowledge bases. However, it is also easy to see that {a mathematical formula}I1⊑I2 implies {a mathematical formula}I2⪰αI1 (for all {a mathematical formula}α∈{f,v,l,p}).
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Corollary 1">
      By exploiting the results from Theorem 1 we obtain the following simple corollary. The expressivity orders wrt. α-characteristics{a mathematical formula}Cα(I,n)({a mathematical formula}α∈{f,v,l,p}) for the inconsistency measures{a mathematical formula}Id,{a mathematical formula}IMI,{a mathematical formula}IMIC,{a mathematical formula}Iη,{a mathematical formula}Ic,{a mathematical formula}ILPm,{a mathematical formula}Imc,{a mathematical formula}Ip,{a mathematical formula}Ihs,{a mathematical formula}IdalalΣ,{a mathematical formula}Idalalmax,{a mathematical formula}Idalalhit,{a mathematical formula}IDf,{a mathematical formula}IPm,{a mathematical formula}Imv, and{a mathematical formula}Incare as shown inFig. 1.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      The proof of the above corollary is omitted as the results follow directly from Theorem 1.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In Fig. 1 the order {a mathematical formula}≻f does not show the placement of the measures {a mathematical formula}IDf, {a mathematical formula}IMIC, and {a mathematical formula}Iη as we only provided upper bounds for the corresponding characteristics in Theorem 1. However, we can give the following partial classification.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Corollary 2">
      For{a mathematical formula}I∈{Ic,ILPm,IdalalΣ,Idalalmax,IPm,Imv},{a mathematical formula}I≻fIDf,{a mathematical formula}I≻fIMIC,{a mathematical formula}I≻fIη.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      The proof of the above corollary is straightforward as, e.g., we provided a finite bound for {a mathematical formula}Cf(Iη,n) (for every n) while {a mathematical formula}Cf(Ic,n) is unbounded. Empirical evidence suggests also the following relationships, but a formal proof has yet to be found.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Conjecture 1">
      {a mathematical formula}IDf≻fIMIC≻fIη≻fIMI.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Fig. 1 shows that the measures {a mathematical formula}IdalalΣ and {a mathematical formula}IPm are the only measures that have maximal expressivity wrt. all four expressivity characteristics (among the considered inconsistency measures) and, as expected, the drastic inconsistency measure {a mathematical formula}Id is the least expressive one. One can also observe that for many measures their positioning in the orders {a mathematical formula}≻v and {a mathematical formula}≻p is complementary, i.e., if a measure has high expressivity wrt. {a mathematical formula}Cf it has low expressivity wrt. {a mathematical formula}Cv (consider e.g. {a mathematical formula}Ic and {a mathematical formula}Ip). This is due to the fact that many measures measure only a specific aspect of inconsistency and usually belong either to the {a mathematical formula}MI-based family of inconsistency measures—which focus on using minimal inconsistent subsets for measuring—or the variable-based family—which focus on conflicting propositions—, cf. [12]. Therefore, they are constrained in their expressivity if one of these dimensions is limited. For example, if the number of formulas in a knowledge base is restricted, so is the number of minimal inconsistent subsets.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Again, it should be noted that expressivity characteristics are meant to complement the investigation of rationality postulates, not to replace them. Rationality postulates are important to analyze the meaningfulness of the values of inconsistency measures, while our characteristics provide a quantitative assessment of their expressivity. However, we believe that the concept of expressivity characteristics and the results reported in this work will nurture general comparative analyses of inconsistency measures.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Proposition 1">
      The expressivity characteristics considered in this paper each tackle one specific aspect of size of a knowledge base. Of course, one can also combine these characteristics to obtain hybrid versions via{a mathematical formula} with {a mathematical formula}α,α′∈{v,f,l,p}, {a mathematical formula}α≠α′, and {a mathematical formula}n,m&gt;0. For example, {a mathematical formula}Cv,f(I,n,m) is the number of different inconsistency values on knowledge bases which mention at most n propositions and consist of at most m formulas. A simple observation on these new characteristics is the following one. Let{a mathematical formula}α,α′∈{v,f,l,p},{a mathematical formula}α≠α′, and{a mathematical formula}n,m&gt;0. Then{a mathematical formula}
